        "name": "SQA acceptance criteria for MRL 2",
        "description": "Commercial solver with vendor-maintained QMS documentation and internal SOP for installation and usage qualification. Gradation 2 requires documented QMS and version control; both confirmed."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/ncv",
      "name": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Code verification performed using manufactured solutions for incompressible Navier-Stokes equations in rotating reference frames. Observed order of convergence 1.94 (theoretical 2.0 for second-order scheme), confirming correct implementation. Lid-driven cavity and Taylor-Couette benchmarks passed to within published reference values. Results documented in solver verification report VR-NCV-2024.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/ncv",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical code verification acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Observed convergence order within 5% of theoretical order for the discretization scheme employed. Benchmark comparison against published analytical/reference solutions with relative error < 1%. Both criteria met."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/disc-error",
      "name": "Discretization error",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study conducted on three systematically refined meshes (2.1M, 8.4M, 33.6M cells, refinement ratio 2). Richardson extrapolation yielded Grid Convergence Index (GCI) of 1.8% for NIH and 2.1% for pressure head on the medium mesh selected for production runs. Asymptotic range confirmed (GCI_fine/GCI_medium × r^p = 1.02 ≈ 1). y+ values maintained between 1 and 5 on all wetted surfaces. Exceeds MRL 2 requirement; Gradation 3 achieved.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/disc-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error acceptance criteria",
        "description": "GCI < 5% on QoIs for the production mesh. Asymptotic convergence confirmed. y+ within recommended range for turbulence model. All criteria met with GCI < 2.1%."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-conditions",
      "name": "Test conditions",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions documented in FDA benchmark protocol. Blood analog fluid (glycerin-water, viscosity 3.5 cP ± 0.1 cP at 37°C) used in experiments; properties directly input to CFD. Flow rates and rotational speeds measured with calibrated instruments (traceable to NIST). Temperature controlled at 37 ± 0.5°C throughout testing. Boundary conditions in CFD set to match measured experimental values with documented uncertainty.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Experimental boundary conditions documented with measurement uncertainty and directly mapped to CFD inputs. NIST-traceable calibration for flow and speed measurements. Temperature control within ±0.5°C. All criteria satisfied."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/output-comparison",
      "name": "Output comparison",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "NIH predictions compared against experimental measurements at all 5 operating points. Mean relative error 8.3%, maximum 13.1%. All predictions within combined experimental and numerical uncertainty bands. Pressure head comparison shows 4.7% mean error. Velocity field comparison (PIV) shows 6.1% normalized RMS error. Systematic bias analysis confirms no directional error trend across operating range. Quantitative comparison metrics documented in validation report VR-OC-2024.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Mean relative error on primary QoI (NIH) < 15%. All predictions within combined uncertainty bands. No systematic bias across operating range. Maximum error < 20%. All criteria met."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/qoi-relevance",
      "name": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), which is the direct regulatory metric for blood pump hemolysis evaluation per FDA guidance. Secondary QoIs (pump head, flow field) are mechanistically linked to hemolysis generation. NIH is computed from the power-law hemolysis model integrating shear stress and exposure time along Lagrangian particle trajectories — directly relevant to clinical outcome of red blood cell damage. QoI selection documented and justified against ASTM F1841 and FDA guidance document.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/qoi-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Primary QoI must be the accepted regulatory metric for the device type and clinical indication. Mechanistic link between QoI and clinical outcome must be documented. Both criteria satisfied."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/val-relevance",
      "name": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Validation experiments performed on the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry used in the COU. Operating conditions span the full COU envelope (2–6 L/min, 2500–4500 RPM). Blood analog fluid properties match clinical CPB conditions. Validation activities directly address the intended use: identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions. The validation scenario is not a simplified surrogate but the actual device geometry and physiologically representative conditions.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/val-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Validation geometry, fluid, and operating conditions must match or bound the COU. Validation must address the primary QoI in the intended use context. Both criteria confirmed."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/solver-error",
      "name": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, separate assessment of numerical solver error beyond code verification and discretization error is not required. The commercial solver's iterative convergence is monitored via residual targets (< 1e-5 for all equations) and flux imbalance (< 0.01%). These are reported in simulation logs but a standalone Gradation assessment is outside the MRL 2 scope. Scoped out per ASME V&V 40 Table 1 guidance for MRL 2 with a verified commercial solver."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/use-error",
      "name": "Use error",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Formal use error assessment is scoped out at MRL 2 for this application. Analyst competency is assured through internal training records, peer review of simulation setup, and independent review of boundary condition assignments. A documented simulation execution checklist was followed for all production runs. Full Gradation-based use error assessment is reserved for MRL 3+ per organizational credibility framework aligned with ASME V&V 40 Table 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-form",
      "name": "Model form",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Formal model form uncertainty assessment is scoped out at MRL 2. The SST k-omega turbulence model was selected based on literature consensus for rotating blood-contacting devices and prior FDA benchmark studies. The power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen et al. coefficients updated per Heuser and Opitz) is the standard for regulatory submissions. Model form choices are documented and justified by reference to published validation studies, but a systematic Gradation-level model form assessment is not required at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-inputs",
      "name": "Model inputs",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Comprehensive model input uncertainty assessment is scoped out at MRL 2. Key inputs (fluid viscosity, density, inlet velocity profiles, rotational speed) are documented with measurement uncertainty and directly traceable to calibrated instruments. Sensitivity of NIH to ±5% variation in each primary input was evaluated informally and showed < 8% response, confirming low sensitivity. Full probabilistic input characterization is deferred to MRL 3 per the credibility plan."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-samples",
      "name": "Test samples",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test sample characterization assessment is scoped out at MRL 2. The FDA generic pump geometry was fabricated to nominal dimensions with manufacturing tolerances documented. A single representative pump unit was used for validation experiments, consistent with FDA benchmark study protocol. Sample-to-sample variability assessment is not required at MRL 2 given the use of the standardized FDA reference geometry."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/input-equivalency",
      "name": "Equivalency of input parameters",
